    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Duo fundamenta Romana[e] magnitudinis: vnum a Romulo humanum: alterum &agrave; Numa divinum. Iacto Numae necessario fundamento, ecc&egrave; Armis deinceps geritur res: et sufficit unus Numa, inter tot Romulos. 
                        Cert&egrave; domi Temperantia, et Iustitia; foris Fortitudine; ubiq[ue] Prudentia, increscebat res Romana.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <person name="Numa Pomplius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>There are two foundations of Roman greatness: first a human one by Romulus, second a divine one by Numa. See how once Numa’s indispensable 
                foundation is thrown out, one acts with arms from then on; and between so many Romuluses one Numa suffices. Surely at home the Roman state became 
                stronger through restraint and justice, abroad through courage, and in all circumstances through prudence.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>An illam pacem, qua[e] sub Numa[e] regno fuit, Deos pra[e]stitisse credendum sit. August. l. 3. c. 9. An optandu[m], quod tanta belloru[m] rabie Romanoru[m] augeretur imperiu[m], cum eo studio, quo sub Numa auctum est, et quietum esse potuit, et tutum. 
                        l. eod. c. 10. De libris Numa[e], quos Senatus iussit incendi, ne sacroru[m] causa[e], quales in eis habebantur, innotescerent. l. 7. c. 34. De hydromantia, per qua[m] Numa, visis quibusdam Daemonum imaginibus, ludificabatur. l. eod. c. 35. 
                        Vbi de Necroma[n]tia, seu Necyomantia. Et ibi L. Vives multa strictissim&egrave;. ) Libri autem Numa[e], qui fuerint, et qua[e] continerent: ecc&egrave; apud Plinium l. 13. c. 13. Vnde veteru[m] secreta nonnihil detecta et praesertim philosophia[e] Pythagorica[e] arcana.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <person name="Juan Luis Vives"/>
                    <person name="Pliny the Elder"/>
                    <person name="Pythagoras"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                    <book title="Natural History"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Whether we are to believe that the peace which prevailed during the reign of Numa was due to the protection of the gods: Augustine, bk. 3, c. 9. Whether it was desirable for the Roman empire to be increased by such a frenzy of warfare when it could have remained quiet 
                and secure by the policy that was pursued under Numa: the same book, c. 10. Of the books of Numa Pompilius, which the Senate ordered to be burned lest the reasons for the sacred rites described in them should become known: bk. 7, c. 34. Of hydromancy, 
                by which Numa was deluded when he saw certain images of the demons: the same book, c. 35. At which place [he writes] about Necromancy, or Necyomantia. At that place Juan Luis Vives also provides much information in the most rigorous way. 
                Yet as for what were Numa’s books and what they contained, see Pliny bk. 13, c. 13. Yet as for what were Numa’s books and what they contained, see Pliny bk. 13, c. 13, where the secrets of the ancients are somewhat revealed and especially the mysteries of 
                Pythagorean philosophy.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Hacten&ugrave;s Numa[e] Historia. Quem Plutarchus scit&egrave; vocat philosophum.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                    <person name="Plutarch"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="curved" text="Historia. Quem Plutarchus scite"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>So far the story of Numa, whom Plutarch expertly calls a philosopher.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>s[upr]a.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Imperatores Romani, successores Romuli, et Ca[e]saris: Pontifices, Numa[e], et Constantini.
                        Summa Populi potestas, et Senatus auctoritas non in regno coepit, sed in interregno. Poste&agrave; Numa, pra[e]ter omnem expectationem creatus Rex, vir sobrius, et pacificus princeps, modestaq[ue] dignitate contentus, nullas abnuerat conditiones seu honorati, 
                        seu honesti imperij. Sat illi publica veneratio: regia maiestas non qua[e]sita. Consuetudo, altera natura, liberum S.P.Q. animauit: et quasi Tyranna super moderatos reges, eos suo more compescuit. Vnde Principatus ciuilis magis, qu&agrave;m augustus: et mixtum potius, 
                        qu&agrave;m merum imperium.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                    <person name="Constantine"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The Roman emperors are the successors to Romulus and Caesar; the priests to Numa and Constantine. The surpreme power of the people and the authority of the senate did not begin during the reign of a king, but in an interregnum. 
                Later, Numa, having been made King completely unexpectedly, did not reject any conditions for either distinguished or honourable rule, as he was a moderate and peaceful ruler, who was satisfied with a modest status. 
                For him public respect was enough; he did not aspire to royal majesty. Habit, a second nature, revived the free Republic, and restrained them in its own manner, like a tyrant facing moderate kings. 
                From which [follows that] the principate was more civic, than majestic, and a mixed form rather than purely autocratic.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
